Secaucus Huber St. School
September 10 at 6:03 AM ¬∑

Good Morning! Today, 9/10, is a Cohort A day. Tomorrow Friday 9/11, will be a Cohort B day.

This is an important message for all students who will be attending school in person. Beginning on Thursday, September 10th, all bus students will enter the school through the gate on the right side of the Main Entrance, located on Paterson Plank Road. All other students will enter through the Main Entrance of the school, also located on Paterson Plank Road. Please be sure to have your mask on and to maintain social distancing. There is no change to how students will exit the school. Thank you, have a day and we look forward to seeing you!

GET READY! GET SET! GO!

CLARENDON'S VIRTUAL FIELD DAY CHALLENGE ~ WEEK OF JUNE 8TH - 12TH

Field Day is a great way to celebrate the end of the school year. It is a fun way to participate in games, activities, and challenges. This year the school will be doing a week long virtual field day with optional activities to complete within the given time.

We will be posting on your google classroom "MINUTE TO WIN IT CHALLENGES" by Mrs. Rodriguez everyday for you to complete. We would love to see how many challenges you can complete throughout the week. #SecaucusPride

Send your videos and photos to Mr. Sommer at esommer@sboe.org to be posted on the Clarendon Facebook and Twitter pages. We can't wait!

post_text: Good Afternoon, this is a message from Jennifer Montesano, Superintendent of Schools for the Secaucus School District. As you may be aware from our district calendar, this Friday, May 22nd, is a one session day for our school district. In order to comply with the state mandates, we will be utilizing a 9am - 1pm schedule on Friday, May 22nd. This day will be dedicated for review and extra help with teachers, as well as, providing students ample time to catch up on school work. Our District will resume its normal schedule on Tuesday, May 26th. We wish all students and their families a safe, happy and healthy Memorial Day weekend!

post_text: Please join us in recognizing May 15th as TSC Awareness Day. TSC or Tuberous Sclerosis Complex is a rare genetic condition that causes noncancerous or benign tumors to grow in the brain or other vital organs. Sclerosis means "hardening of tissue" and tubers are root shaped growths. TSC affects approximately 1 million people worldwide. Many of those affected are children. While there is no cure for TSC there are treatments available for the symptoms. For more information about TSC please visit tsalliance.org.

Secaucus Clarendon School added 292 new photos to the album: Clarendon's Virtual Spirit Week 2020 ~ SGO Sponsored.
April 27 at 11:14 AM ¬∑

This week the Clarendon SGO hosted a Virtual Spirit Week. Our Clarendon bees had a great time participating in so many fun activities. Keep up the great work bees! #SecaucusPride

"Pajama Day"
On Monday, 4/27, students were encouraged to wear comfy pajamas while continuing their distance learning. Way to go bees!

‚ÄúSuperhero Day‚Äù
On Tuesday, 4/28, students were encouraged to wear a shirt that honors our real life and fictional heroes .

"Wellness Wednesday"
On Wednesday, 4/29, students were encouraged to wear comfy clothes and go for a walk with their family.

"Disney Day"
On Thursday, 4/30, students were encouraged to wear their favorite Disney shirt or accessory.

"Happy BEE Day: Clarendon Bees Rock"
On Friday, 5/01, students were encouraged to rock your Clarendon school colors/gear to show your school pride.

All K-5 students in the Secaucus School District will be participating in Virtual learning for the week of March 16th, due to a mandated school closure. All students/parents have received a join code for their teacher's Google Classroom through e-mail. Using your child's "students.sboe.org" google email address, you will be required to log-on to the Google Classroom each day to receive the student's assignment and inform the teacher through a discussion feed that the student is present. Please e-mail your child's teacher for more detailed information. The K-5 website is availible here: https://sites.google.com/sboe.org/coronaviruscovid-19/secaucus-response-to-covid-19/instructional-plan-grades-prek-5?authuser=0

The Secaucus High School Consumer Bowl Team has captured its 2nd consecutive championship over High-Tech High School, in the Hudson County competition of the New Jersey Division of Consumer Affairs Consumer Bowl.

The Competition took place on January 14, 2020 at Secaucus High School. The New Jersey High School Consumer Bowl is an educational competition for high school students across the state meant to educate young adults on a variety of consumer and business issues.

The SHS team will go on to the Northern Regional Competition, which will take place in April.

This year‚Äôs team consists of Senior Captain Janan Lacka, Juniors Ergen Banja and Zarrar Nawaz, Sophomore Rebecca Luz Soler, and Senior Joan Banks. The Business Club/Consumer Bowl advisor is Ms. Alexis Chisari, Business and Technology Teacher at Secaucus High School. To find out more about the Consumer Bowl, please go to www.njconsumeraffairs.gov.

This gives Secaucus its 4th Hudson County championship in the last five years.

Costantino Captures Patriot Invitational Title

Freshman Dean Costantino took 1st place in the 120lb weight class at the 20th Annual Patriot Invitational. Costantino beat Ernesto McRae of Bloomfield by a score of 5 - 4 in the semifinals.
In the finals Costantino would go on to defeat Rob Danza of Lakeland by a score of 12 - 6.

Secaucus had four other wrestlers medal: Carlos Triana (2nd), Anthony Costantino (2nd), Massimo Iacopelli (2nd), and Tyler Giraldo (3rd).

Ilias Siafakas is at Secaucus High School.
December 23, 2019 at 11:57 AM ¬∑ Secaucus, NJ ¬∑

Im so beyond proud of my students for this performance of True Colors by Cyndi Lauper. I might be biased, but I think it‚Äôs truly remarkable!

Music teachers by nature are always looking for ways to help improve their students, which means always looking for faults. A dear close friend and colleague of mine gave me the best feedback for this performance. He said, ‚ÄúWhile listening, I was able to stop judging, nit-picking, and error-detecting. I found myself moved to a point that all of that stuff didn't register. Pure enjoyment.‚Äù

That is quite possibly the best feedback to receive. Thanks for such kind words Sean! I learned from the best! üòä

And thanks Jessica for the video!!!!
